column1: #Text=Egyptian prime minister steps down ; armed forces appoint former transport minister to position
#Text=Ahmed Shafik , Egypt 's acting prime minister , has resigned , the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces , now in control of the country , announced yesterday .

#Text=Shafik was appointed to his position by then Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak during the 2011 Egypt anti-government protests , not long before Mubarak decided to resign as president on February 11 , 2011 .
#Text=Meanwhile , a number of his cabinet ministers have retained their positions .
#Text=Shafik had received criticism for his negative attitude towards young protesters and his " inadequate vision " , according to the Los Angeles Times .

column1: #Text=In response to the announcement of Shafik 's resignation , Wael Ghonim , a Google executive , credited with organizing the first demonstration and a former political prisoner , wrote on Twitter , a micro-blogging website , " Power to the people ! "
#Text=During the Egyptian protests , one of the key demands of the protesters was that Shafik step down from his acting minister status .
#Text=Mohamed ElBaradei , another pro-democracy activist and co-recipient of the Nobel Peace Prize , tweeted on Twitter that Egypt is " on the right track . "
#Text=Did Ahmed Shafik make the correct decision to resign ?
#Text=Is Essam Sharaf the right person to be prime minister ?
#Text=The statement released by the Council also announced Essam Sharaf as the new prime minister .
